WEBVTT

00:00.386 --> 00:05.793
The scripture reading today is from the book of Genesis, chapter 29, verses 15 through 35.

00:07.415 --> 00:12.142
Laban said to him, just because you were a relative of mine, should you work for me for nothing?

00:12.182 --> 00:14.044
Tell me what your wages should be.

00:14.845 --> 00:16.167
Now, Laban had two daughters.

00:16.588 --> 00:19.832
The name of the older was Leah, and the name of the younger was Rachel.

00:20.353 --> 00:23.116
Leah had weak eyes, but Rachel had a lovely figure.

00:23.157 --> 00:23.777
It was beautiful.

00:24.478 --> 00:30.226
Jacob was in love with Rachel and said, I'll work for you for seven years in return for your younger daughter, Rachel.

00:31.202 --> 00:34.485
Laban said, it's better that I give her to you than to some other man.

00:34.885 --> 00:35.546
Stay here with me."

00:36.487 --> 00:41.932
So Jacob served seven years to get Rachel, but they seemed like only a few days to him because of his love for her.

00:42.913 --> 00:45.175
Then Jacob said to Laban, give me my wife.

00:45.355 --> 00:47.597
My time is complete, and I want to make love to her.

00:48.258 --> 00:52.041
So Laban brought together all the people of the place and gave a great feast.

00:52.662 --> 00:57.366
But when evening came, he took his daughter Leah and brought her to Jacob, and Jacob made love to her.

00:58.067 --> 01:01.170
And Laban gave his servant Silpa to his daughter as her attendant.

01:02.050 --> 01:03.793
When morning came, there was Leah.

01:04.313 --> 01:07.378
So Jacob said to Laban, what is this you've done to me?

01:07.859 --> 01:09.381
I served you for Rachel, didn't I?

01:09.421 --> 01:10.803
Why have you deceived me?

01:11.724 --> 01:15.850
Laban replied, it is not our custom to give the younger daughter in marriage before the older one.

01:16.451 --> 01:22.180
Finish this daughter's bridal week, then we will give you the younger one also in return for another seven years of work.

01:23.501 --> 01:24.423
And Jacob did so.

01:24.904 --> 01:29.330
He finished the week with Leah, and then Laban gave him his daughter Rachel to be his wife.

01:29.794 --> 01:33.039
Laban gave his servant Bilha to his daughter Rachel as her attendant.

01:33.740 --> 01:37.866
Jacob made love to Rachel also, and his love for Rachel was greater than his love for Leah.

01:38.447 --> 01:40.270
And he worked for Laban another seven years.

01:41.552 --> 01:46.539
When the Lord saw that Leah was not loved, he enabled her to conceive, but Rachel remained childless.

01:47.301 --> 01:49.264
Leah became pregnant and gave birth to a son.

01:50.005 --> 01:54.111
She named him Ruben, for she said, it is because the Lord has seen my misery.

01:54.411 --> 01:56.114
Surely my husband will love me now.

01:56.834 --> 02:03.804
She conceived again, and when she gave birth to another son, she said, because the Lord heard that I am not loved, he gave me this one too.

02:03.844 --> 02:05.747
So she named him Simeon.

02:06.889 --> 02:14.621
Again, she conceived, and when she gave birth to yet another son, she said, now at last my husband will become attached to me because I have borne him three sons.

02:15.362 --> 02:16.403
So he was named Levi.

02:17.325 --> 02:22.593
She conceived again, and when she gave birth to a son, she said, this time I will praise the Lord.

02:23.213 --> 02:26.258
So she named him Judah, that she stopped having children.

02:26.722 --> 02:27.783
This is the word of the Lord.

02:35.250 --> 02:35.951
Thanks, Natalie.

02:36.552 --> 02:37.352
Isn't she great?

02:38.914 --> 02:40.115
Good morning, Antioch.

02:40.235 --> 02:47.422
My name is Linda, and I'm the family taster here, which means I get to spend a lot of time with the kids and teenagers at our church.

02:47.542 --> 02:50.885
But this morning, I'm excited because we get to spend the morning together.

02:51.686 --> 02:55.570
We are continuing our study through the book of Genesis, and we have

02:55.682 --> 02:57.825
quite the story to dive into this morning.

02:58.346 --> 03:00.650
But first, let's do a quick review of where we are.

03:00.690 --> 03:06.018
As we've talked about, the story of the Bible can be broken down into a six act play.

03:06.559 --> 03:10.245
In act one, God creates the world and it's incredible.

03:10.305 --> 03:15.473
In act two, sin enters the world and everything starts falling apart.

03:16.234 --> 03:18.197
But thankfully, this is not the end of the story.

03:18.798 --> 03:23.826
Act three zooms in on one particular family, Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.

03:24.450 --> 03:31.201
This is the family whom God has chosen to redeem the world and everything in it back to himself.

03:32.402 --> 03:35.087
This is the family that eventually Jesus will be born into.

03:35.147 --> 03:40.475
Now, you might assume that as God's chosen family, they would have their act together.

03:40.996 --> 03:44.040
But as we've seen, this family is a mess.

03:44.061 --> 03:52.754
Their history is full of things like deception, hatred, rape, murder, slavery, and even war.

03:53.538 --> 03:59.267
This is not a model family, but they are the family that God chose to be his people.

04:00.208 --> 04:14.250
And their sin and dysfunction proved to us that no matter how broken, backwards and messed up we get or the story gets, God will never stop pursuing his people with a never ending unstoppable love.

04:15.452 --> 04:18.156
And today's story shows us the same thing again.

04:18.417 --> 04:21.842
So grab your Bible and open to Genesis 29.

04:22.562 --> 04:25.787
So far in Genesis, we've had a lot of stories about brothers.

04:25.847 --> 04:29.833
We've had Cain and Abel, Isaac and Ishmael, Jacob and Isha.

04:30.594 --> 04:33.819
But today, our story is about two sisters.

04:34.520 --> 04:36.142
Their names are Rachel and Leah.

04:36.703 --> 04:42.732
And in Genesis 29, there's a mister who comes between these two sisters.

04:43.854 --> 04:47.439
Here's what we're told about them in verse 16.

04:48.120 --> 04:49.643
Now, Laven had two daughters.

04:50.223 --> 04:51.986
The name of the older was Leah.

04:52.322 --> 04:53.884
And the name of the younger was Rachel.

04:54.844 --> 04:59.109
Leah had weak eyes, but Rachel had a lovely figure and was beautiful.

05:00.450 --> 05:04.654
So Rachel is the younger of the two sisters, and she's a pretty one.

05:05.215 --> 05:07.297
We're told she had a lovely figure and was beautiful.

05:07.497 --> 05:14.264
But before you start stereotyping her, you should also know that in verse nine, we're told that Rachel is a shepherd.

05:14.864 --> 05:16.245
So she's not some bimbo.

05:16.286 --> 05:20.850
She's a hardworking farm girl who happens to get the good looks in her family.

05:22.114 --> 05:24.717
Leah, on the other hand, not so much.

05:25.698 --> 05:28.962
We don't know exactly what it means that she had weak eyes.

05:29.022 --> 05:32.406
It might mean that her eyes are abnormally light in color.

05:32.466 --> 05:36.231
It might mean that she was visually impaired and couldn't see very well.

05:37.192 --> 05:40.736
Or it might mean that she had crazy eyes and looked a little strange.

05:41.337 --> 05:48.946
But whatever it meant, Leah's weak eyes made her the less attractive, the less desired of the two sisters.

05:50.082 --> 05:51.764
So that's who Leah and Rachel are.

05:51.844 --> 05:59.295
And somehow, these two sisters end up in a strange love triangle with the same guy, their cousin, Jacob.

06:00.516 --> 06:02.399
Last week, Pete introduced us to Jacob.

06:02.859 --> 06:04.962
He saw his less hairy twin brother.

06:04.982 --> 06:08.948
A few years have passed and now Jacob is 40 years old.

06:08.968 --> 06:16.498
And after stealing the family's birthright and blessing from his brother, Jacob flees town and heads off to a distant land.

06:17.378 --> 06:22.965
Eventually, tired and thirsty from traveling through the desert, he comes to a well.

06:23.926 --> 06:25.227
And he stops to get a drink.

06:26.369 --> 06:30.313
And there at the well, Jacob sees Rachel for the first time.

06:30.974 --> 06:36.461
This drop dead gorgeous shepherd girl who's there to get water for her sheep.

06:36.481 --> 06:43.189
Now, I don't know if Jacob has ever talked to a girl before or what, but here's what he does.

06:43.249 --> 06:44.210
Look at verse 10.

06:45.058 --> 06:55.930
When Jacob saw Rachel, daughter of his uncle, Laban, and Laban's sheep, he went over and rolled the stone away from the mouth of the well and watered his uncle's sheep.

06:57.372 --> 07:01.016
So Jacob sees this beautiful woman and decides he's going to impress her.

07:01.476 --> 07:13.810
So instead of grabbing a couple of other shepherds to help him move this huge stone from the top of the well, Jacob kisses his biceps and then grunts and strains and he rolls it off by himself.

07:14.114 --> 07:15.496
feeling pretty proud of himself.

07:16.017 --> 07:18.740
He walks over to Rachel and he makes his move.

07:19.501 --> 07:26.370
Verse 11 says, then Jacob kissed Rachel and began to weep aloud.

07:26.430 --> 07:27.812
Right?

07:27.992 --> 07:28.893
This is ridiculous.

07:29.214 --> 07:41.490
This 40-year-old man covered in dust from running 500 miles through the desert sees a pretty girl at the well, tries to impress her by moving this huge rock, then walks over, kisses her,

07:41.570 --> 07:45.135
but gets so overwhelmed that he starts crying.

07:45.155 --> 07:47.860
This is so awkward.

07:47.900 --> 07:49.382
I can't even imagine it.

07:49.402 --> 07:54.350
It reminds me of my freshman year of college at Moody Bible Institute.

07:55.491 --> 08:05.066
There were a bunch of sheltered missionary kids who'd been homeschooled and apparently had never talked to a girl before, but they went to Bible school to get their MRS degree.

08:05.567 --> 08:10.354
Now, my dad had warned me about this, but I thought he was joking until not one.

08:10.786 --> 08:16.574
Not two, but three different guys proposed to me without even asking me on a first date.

08:17.976 --> 08:24.525
That is why they called it Moody Bridal Institute, Ring by Spring or your money back.

08:24.685 --> 08:32.456
I imagine Jacob had that vibe in this story, just totally awkward, intense, and immature.

08:33.517 --> 08:38.044
Side note to all you teenage boys, this is not how you ask a girl out.

08:38.564 --> 08:39.826
This doesn't usually work.

08:40.482 --> 08:44.607
But the funny thing is that apparently it worked for Jacob.

08:45.268 --> 08:49.533
This isn't what I would have been looking for, but Rachel isn't freaked out.

08:49.914 --> 08:53.038
In fact, she brings Jacob home to meet her father.

08:53.078 --> 08:56.943
And Jacob hits it off with her dad, his uncle, Laban.

08:57.784 --> 09:00.788
Laban tells Jacob he can stay with him for a while if he wants.

09:01.869 --> 09:06.355
But after a month, Laban realizes that Jacob doesn't seem to be going anywhere.

09:06.375 --> 09:09.138
And all he wants is to marry Rachel.

09:09.698 --> 09:12.363
But Jacob's not really in a position to take a wife.

09:12.763 --> 09:20.256
You see, he's broke as a joke and all he has are the clothes on his back and his walking stick.

09:20.276 --> 09:25.405
So, Laban and Jacob make a deal that Jacob will work for Laban for seven years.

09:26.126 --> 09:29.351
And in exchange, Laban will let him marry Rachel.

09:29.872 --> 09:30.994
So that's what Jacob did.

09:31.515 --> 09:35.762
In verse 20, we see, so Jacob served seven years to get Rachel.

09:36.034 --> 09:39.938
But they seemed like only a few days to him because of his love for her.

09:41.119 --> 09:42.100
Come on, Jacob.

09:42.140 --> 09:44.682
You don't need to be that cheesy about this.

09:44.702 --> 09:45.503
We get it.

09:45.543 --> 09:47.465
You're so in love with her.

09:48.446 --> 09:49.307
But Jacob does it.

09:49.787 --> 09:56.133
He works for seven years, twice as long as was customary at that time, so that he could marry Rachel.

09:57.314 --> 10:00.958
Seven years pass, and sure enough, the wedding day has finally come.

10:01.639 --> 10:05.202
The entire town comes to celebrate Jacob and Rachel.

10:05.314 --> 10:06.976
Everything is going great.

10:07.536 --> 10:08.817
The vibes are strong.

10:08.857 --> 10:10.659
The bride looks like a million bucks.

10:11.260 --> 10:14.002
The food is amazing and there's great drink and dancing.

10:14.022 --> 10:16.004
Everything is perfect.

10:16.785 --> 10:21.309
Then, while the party is still going, Jacob and his new bride slip away from the crowd.

10:22.090 --> 10:26.274
He takes her back to the tent and they enjoy their wedding night together.

10:27.535 --> 10:29.978
But here's where the twist in the story comes in.

10:30.859 --> 10:34.322
In verse 25, when morning came,

10:34.530 --> 10:36.032
There was Leah.

10:36.652 --> 10:39.555
So Jacob said to Laban, what is this that you have done to me?

10:39.575 --> 10:42.118
I served you for Rachel, didn't I?

10:42.898 --> 10:45.281
Why have you deceived me?

10:46.662 --> 10:56.392
So the morning after the wedding, Jacob rolls over in bed and starts snuggling the woman next to him, then opens his eyes to take in his beautiful new bride.

10:57.213 --> 11:02.258
But to his shock, there's Leah with her crazy eyes and her morning breath.

11:03.298 --> 11:08.243
Obviously, it must have been really dark in that tent the night before.

11:08.303 --> 11:14.549
Or maybe Jacob had a little too much to drink at the wedding and had his beer goggles on.

11:14.609 --> 11:17.632
But either way, can you imagine the surprise?

11:17.692 --> 11:23.177
So Jacob puts on his bathrobe and he marches out of the tent to track down Laban.

11:24.018 --> 11:26.520
His father-in-law has pulled a fast one on him.

11:27.341 --> 11:32.786
Laban was the one who somehow disguised Leah and sent her into the tent with Jacob.

11:34.050 --> 11:43.480
What's interesting is that if you remember, Jacob is something of a con man himself, but now the trickster has been tricked.

11:44.421 --> 11:50.148
The deceiver has been deceived and Jacob is furious with his father-in-law.

11:51.409 --> 12:01.200
But Laban replied in verse 26, it's not our custom here to give the younger daughter in marriage before the older one, finish this daughter's bridal week.

12:01.220 --> 12:03.282
Then we will give you the younger one also.

12:03.554 --> 12:05.996
in return for another seven years of work.

12:07.177 --> 12:08.979
So Laban makes Jacob an offer.

12:09.560 --> 12:14.024
Now that you've married Leah, work for me for another seven years and you can have Rachel too.

12:14.064 --> 12:22.892
Even though he'd gotten ripped off, Jacob is so smitten with Rachel that he agreed to work for another seven years.

12:23.993 --> 12:33.202
So Jacob finally marries Rachel and now he has two wives, sister wives, the woman that he loves and her less attractive

12:33.378 --> 12:34.119
older sister.

12:34.159 --> 12:37.902
This is obviously a recipe for disaster.

12:39.143 --> 12:50.874
It's interesting that later on in Leviticus, the Israelites have a law that says, while your wife is living, do not marry her sister and have sexual relations with her, for they would be rivals.

12:52.136 --> 13:00.704
I think there's a good chance they made this law after hearing the story of Rachel and Leah, because that's exactly what happens.

13:01.224 --> 13:03.346
These two sisters become rivals.

13:03.618 --> 13:07.544
and things get especially complicated when babies come into the story.

13:08.786 --> 13:17.339
Verse 31 says, when the Lord saw that Leah was not loved, he enabled her to conceive, but Rachel remained childless.

13:18.962 --> 13:27.315
So after all the drama that led these two sisters to marry the same man, Jacob loves Rachel, but Leah is not loved.

13:28.236 --> 13:31.922
Not only was she less beautiful than her sister,

13:32.290 --> 13:37.758
Not only had her father deceitfully gotten rid of her, she is unloved by her husband.

13:38.519 --> 13:42.164
She's a debt to pay off so her husband can sleep with another woman.

13:42.204 --> 13:47.632
And her little sister, the beauty queen of the family, is the one he's in love with.

13:48.594 --> 13:49.955
Can you imagine the pain of it?

13:51.658 --> 13:56.905
But it's here in verse 31 that God is mentioned for the first time in this story.

13:57.546 --> 14:00.050
God sees that Leah is unloved.

14:00.322 --> 14:03.646
So God shows her favor and enables her to have children.

14:04.908 --> 14:10.594
Now Leah eventually has seven babies, but our passage today focuses on the birth of our first four.

14:11.375 --> 14:20.066
I wanna spend a few minutes looking at the names Leah gives to these babies and what those names reveal about what is going on inside of her.

14:20.847 --> 14:29.938
We'll see that amid all the rejection, rivalry, deception, and pain, God is at work in Leah's heart.

14:30.338 --> 14:36.487
revealing himself and developing her into a woman of strength, conviction, and joy.

14:37.649 --> 14:43.177
So let's meet Leah's first four babies and see what they teach us about the story of her heart.

14:44.419 --> 14:45.460
We read in verse 32.

14:47.163 --> 14:49.727
Leah became pregnant and gave birth to a son.

14:49.787 --> 14:54.654
She named him Ruben for she said, it's because the Lord has seen my misery.

14:55.255 --> 14:57.458
Surely my husband will love me now.

14:58.690 --> 15:06.878
Leah names her first baby, Ruben, because in Hebrew, the name Ruben sounds like the word for misery, which isn't a very cute baby name.

15:07.639 --> 15:11.502
Can you imagine what it was like to introduce her new child to her friends and family?

15:11.542 --> 15:15.426
They, ooh, and they, ah, then they ask, what's his name?

15:16.427 --> 15:18.289
And she said, misery?

15:18.349 --> 15:21.151
This is where Leah is.

15:21.432 --> 15:22.453
She's miserable.

15:22.973 --> 15:25.916
She's the third wheel in Rachel and Jacob's marriage.

15:26.777 --> 15:28.018
Her husband doesn't love her.

15:28.610 --> 15:39.844
She's miserable, but she's hoping to have a baby and that this will change things for her because she lives in a culture where women become more valuable when they bring children into the world.

15:40.785 --> 15:46.171
So she's counting on this baby to change her miserable existence.

15:46.191 --> 15:48.454
Surely her husband will love her now, right?

15:50.076 --> 15:52.639
But Ruben is born and nothing changes.

15:53.260 --> 15:54.341
She's still miserable.

15:55.983 --> 15:58.386
Then in verse 33, she conceived again.

15:59.170 --> 16:04.758
And when she gave birth to a son, she said, because the Lord heard that I am not loved, she gave me this one too.

16:05.439 --> 16:06.781
So she named him Simeon.

16:08.263 --> 16:12.349
She names her second child Simeon, which in Hebrew means he hears.

16:13.650 --> 16:15.673
This is the longing of Leah's heart.

16:16.114 --> 16:17.716
She longs to be heard.

16:17.736 --> 16:19.979
Have you ever felt unheard?

16:20.039 --> 16:23.865
It's one of the most dehumanizing experiences.

16:24.826 --> 16:27.570
I heard someone say that being unheard

16:27.778 --> 16:32.843
feels so much like being unloved that the average person can't tell the difference.

16:33.724 --> 16:41.192
Or say it the other way, being heard feels so much like being loved that the average person can't tell the difference.

16:42.454 --> 16:46.658
But Leah is unheard and therefore unloved.

16:48.220 --> 16:50.222
So she calls her child Simeon.

16:50.623 --> 16:51.143
He hears.

16:51.844 --> 16:57.490
Hoping that after bearing Jacob two sons, he might finally notice her and love her.

16:58.242 --> 16:59.564
but he doesn't.

17:00.926 --> 17:04.190
Then in verse 34, again she conceived.

17:04.611 --> 17:12.242
And when she gave birth to a son, she said, now at last, my husband will become attached to me because I have born him three sons.

17:13.123 --> 17:14.505
So she named him Levi.

17:15.687 --> 17:19.031
After giving birth to her third son, the baby is placed in her arms.

17:19.853 --> 17:22.957
She names him Levi, which means attached.

17:24.319 --> 17:26.482
Leah longs to be attached.

17:26.850 --> 17:31.094
She's tired of being alone, isolated, and abandoned.

17:32.095 --> 17:42.025
With each baby, she hopes her husband will finally love her, that he will see her, that he will love her, and that he will attach himself to her instead of her sister.

17:42.965 --> 17:48.451
But after birthing three boys, she's still alone, unwanted, and unloved.

17:50.012 --> 17:53.576
Now she has these three kids whose names mean, I'm miserable.

17:53.596 --> 17:56.018
My husband doesn't hear me.

17:56.386 --> 17:58.148
and my husband isn't attached to me.

17:59.189 --> 18:02.794
It must have been an awkward mom moment when she went to sign them up for school.

18:03.314 --> 18:04.416
You named your kids what?

18:06.358 --> 18:08.781
These names are heartbreaking.

18:09.422 --> 18:15.289
They tell a story of a woman whose only hope is to win the love of a man who doesn't want her.

18:16.971 --> 18:20.315
But then Leah gets pregnant for a fourth time.

18:21.036 --> 18:22.898
And this time something's different.

18:23.202 --> 18:27.950
Something happens in Leah between the births of her third and fourth sons.

18:28.911 --> 18:31.836
We don't know what, but something changes in her.

18:32.717 --> 18:35.341
Verse 35, she conceived again.

18:35.361 --> 18:41.511
And when she gave birth to a son, she said, this time I will praise the Lord.

18:42.333 --> 18:43.715
So she named him Judah.

18:45.017 --> 18:48.242
She names her fourth baby Judah, which means praise God.

18:49.122 --> 18:58.255
Instead of a sad and depressing name like her other children have, Judah is a name of hope, gratitude, and joy.

19:00.097 --> 19:14.998
Again, we don't know what changed in Leah between her third and fourth kids, but in naming this baby Judah, she is celebrating that she is no longer stuck in the cycle of pain and discontentment that has marked her life for years.

19:15.739 --> 19:17.842
She says, this time,

19:18.082 --> 19:19.664
I will praise the Lord."

19:21.807 --> 19:25.573
Do you know that Leah is the first person in the Bible to praise God?

19:26.735 --> 19:37.751
She's the first to experience such overwhelming contentment and joy in God that she rejoices, not just for what God has done, but for who God is.

19:37.811 --> 19:47.986
Somehow, in the midst of her loneliness and despair, God meets Leah in a way that changes her forever.

19:48.674 --> 19:51.857
See, nothing about her circumstances had changed.

19:52.418 --> 19:54.980
She didn't win the lottery or witness a miracle.

19:55.501 --> 19:57.063
She still got her crazy eyes.

19:57.123 --> 20:00.486
Her stupid husband is still oblivious to her, except in bed.

20:00.506 --> 20:03.689
Nothing has changed around her.

20:06.372 --> 20:10.116
Instead, something has changed in her.

20:11.237 --> 20:16.242
She's experienced God in a way that meets the deepest need of her soul.

20:16.834 --> 20:27.551
She thought that by having more kids, she would finally find the love of her life and that her deepest desires to be loved, to be heard, and to be attached would be satisfied.

20:28.752 --> 20:36.985
But eventually she realizes that neither her husband nor any other person could ever truly satisfy her.

20:38.247 --> 20:42.734
She finally saw that only God was enough.

20:44.757 --> 20:45.298
By the way,

20:45.474 --> 20:57.370
I know that some of us here today know exactly what it feels like to be Leah, to feel unwanted, unknown, or unattached, especially those of us who are single and don't want to be.

20:58.672 --> 21:06.442
I also know that the church isn't the easiest place to be unmarried with all the couples and the families and the weddings and the child dedications.

21:07.243 --> 21:12.190
If you're single, I want you to know that you are seen and you are loved.

21:13.632 --> 21:15.154
Not only are you wanted,

21:15.490 --> 21:17.813
in this family of God, but you are needed.

21:18.633 --> 21:19.835
You're not second class here.

21:19.875 --> 21:26.882
The Bible has a very high view of marriage, but I would argue it has an even higher view of singleness.

21:27.663 --> 21:40.777
So I hope you can take comfort in knowing that even though technically Leah was married, her value and identity weren't based on another person, but on being heard, understood, and loved by God.

21:42.519 --> 21:43.640
So God loves Leah.

21:43.941 --> 21:45.202
God hears Leah.

21:45.378 --> 21:47.961
God is attached to Leah and will never leave her.

21:48.001 --> 21:52.687
And when she realizes this, she praises God.

21:53.828 --> 21:59.395
See, the turning point in this story is not when Leah finally gets what she wants.

22:00.216 --> 22:04.201
It's when she realizes that she has had it all along.

22:06.123 --> 22:11.570
We might not put our hope in the same things Leah did, but we're all prone to do this in our own way.

22:11.938 --> 22:16.644
We might be looking to that next promotion at work or that solution to a health problem.

22:16.684 --> 22:19.908
It might be that car or that house or that spouse.

22:20.368 --> 22:27.197
We hope will finally cause us to feel satisfied because deep down, we are all Leah.

22:27.697 --> 22:28.739
We all do this.

22:29.259 --> 22:41.394
We all look to something or someone for approval and worth and end up disappointed and miserable until we look to God to satisfy our deepest needs.

22:42.722 --> 22:44.344
So what is that thing for you?

22:45.826 --> 22:53.195
What is that thing that teases and tantalizes you and makes you feel like you need it or your life will be miserable?

22:55.097 --> 23:01.285
Because just like Leah, the turning point in our story is not when we get what we want.

23:02.446 --> 23:05.810
It's when we realize we had it all along.

23:07.042 --> 23:19.174
And when we, like Leah, lean into God's love for us, like really lean in and let it shape who we are and how we live, we will find that we can praise God too.

23:20.355 --> 23:31.306
Even when our body doesn't look the way we want it to, even when our family of origin has hurt us, even when our relationships fall apart, even when life isn't going the way you've imagined.

23:32.567 --> 23:35.570
God's love for us is big enough.

23:35.650 --> 23:38.575
to hold us no matter what happens.

23:40.017 --> 23:41.439
I know because it's happened to me.

23:41.479 --> 23:44.484
I actually have a special connection with this story.

23:44.624 --> 23:48.850
Most of you know, just like Leah, I also have a son named Judah.

23:49.531 --> 23:54.699
What you don't know though, is that we chose his name for the exact opposite reasons of Leah.

23:55.340 --> 23:59.587
See, Leah was a young married woman desperate to have kids.

24:00.468 --> 24:04.114
But when Travis and I first got married 15 years ago, I was

24:04.194 --> 24:08.361
terrified of the idea of having kids, especially the boy kind.

24:09.142 --> 24:13.108
I was pretty sure I never wanted to have kids, so that was our plan.

24:13.829 --> 24:19.178
But despite three forms of birth control in October of 2010, we found out we were pregnant.

24:19.799 --> 24:22.944
And I was sick puking every single day.

24:22.964 --> 24:28.993
We went to the 20-week ultrasound and learned that our first child was a boy.

24:29.895 --> 24:32.018
And as we drove home from the doctor that day,

24:32.354 --> 24:43.629
Travis, knowing this story in Genesis 29, suggested we name him Judah to choose to praise God despite our fears.

24:45.031 --> 24:48.095
And of course, now I can't imagine life without Judah.

24:48.496 --> 24:52.161
We adore him and we marvel at his brilliant mind and his boundless energy.

24:52.662 --> 24:58.970
He's our Judah, and we praise God, not only for him, but for our Josiah also, who came along a few years later.

24:59.831 --> 25:01.874
It wasn't a part of my plan.

25:02.210 --> 25:05.434
But now I love our little family and am so thankful for our boys.

25:07.177 --> 25:11.342
In closing, I want to draw your attention to one more part of this story.

25:12.564 --> 25:17.331
For my entire childhood, hearing this story made me want to be Rachel.

25:17.931 --> 25:20.535
After all, she was attractive and she got the boy.

25:20.595 --> 25:25.982
But as I've taken a deep dive into this story, I see I had it all wrong.

25:27.024 --> 25:31.730
If you jump to Genesis 35, you'll see how things ended for the sisters.

25:32.322 --> 25:38.430
There you see Jacob, Rachel, and Leah, and their clan of kids moving back to Jacob's hometown.

25:39.671 --> 25:42.535
Rachel is pregnant, and she goes into labor mid-journey.

25:43.296 --> 25:44.577
But the labor is terrible.

25:45.278 --> 25:51.927
And as she takes her last breath, she names her son Ben-O-Nai, which means son of my trouble.

25:53.368 --> 25:55.571
And they bury her by the side of the road.

25:56.913 --> 25:58.034
This isn't the dream.

25:59.716 --> 26:01.138
Maybe all along,

26:01.794 --> 26:03.276
It was actually Leah.

26:04.197 --> 26:13.829
Even though the road was rough in the end, she's the one who found a reason to say, this time, I will praise the Lord.

26:15.571 --> 26:20.717
Because unlike the bad fathers in our story today, God is a good father.

26:21.458 --> 26:23.540
He doesn't withhold his love from us.

26:24.682 --> 26:27.705
Instead, he gives us his son.

26:28.927 --> 26:31.570
In Jesus, he has come to rescue

26:31.650 --> 26:33.236
and redeem all things.

26:34.220 --> 26:39.602
God loves us that much, and His love is enough.

